title: Works great!
text:
Top it off (gloss) is a big hit. It does a great job with sealing your gel manicure and lasting a long time. I appreciate that isn’t too thick and gloppy.

The matte top coat is an odd duck. It’s not suuuuper-matte, but it works really well for my purposes. I have a crazy nail (after a little accident) with a thin vertical strip that constantly splits. If you imagine that would be painful, you would be correct, so I cover that nail in clear gel polish. The matte-ness is pretty close to the sheen of a natural nail so it’s not immediately obvious unless you look super close (and even then). So I don’t have to wear nail polish if I don’t want to, but if I do, I can just paint regular polish over this. And if you use a non-acetone polish remover, you can even switch shades without this coming off.

The only reason I knock off a star is because the matte isn’t impervious, and it will pick up fabric dyes and other colorants fairly easily. Sometimes I’ll look down and notice that one nail is looking pretty grey (like the lenses on sunglasses), which is frustrating.

Take off is not too bad. Those crazy clips that hold cotton pads to your fingertips and some acetone will make short work of this in about 15 minutes with no scratching that damages your nail plate. People whine that gel is bad for your nails, but if I remove it properly, it doesn’t hurt them a bit, at least not in my experience. In fact, my nails grow pretty long and strong with this on.

title: Nice change from plain hair ties
text:
Inexpensive and cute way to change up from the same old elastic hair bands anytime you want to put your hair up. The ties with the longer ends look better than the ones with the little short ones, so the short ones are those I tend to wear only around the house. Stretch is good, and there is enough fabric around the elastic that you don't risk tears when putting in your hair. I've laundered these every so often over the last year, and they come through just fine.

Ignore the part of the listing that claims you get 75 pieces as you only get 10. title: In all fairness....
text:
I got these quickly and they are great...yes they are only slightly , almost imperceivably, thinner than the Konad plates, maybe it's not so much the thickness as the type of stainess steel they use..Konad's seem to be slightly more rigid, less apt to bend or dent the plate, but both brands of plates should be cared for and used gently, it can happen to either brand. Maybe they have improved their processess but I didn't find the edges overly sharp or ragged, after all they are a thin piece of metal like the top of an aluminum can and it's true, it's possible, you could cut yourself on the plates but it's not a toy and it's more like a craft or makeup item and not intended for kids to handle carelessly. You wouldn't want a toddler getting into glue or nail polish remover type of products either.
As far as transferring the images goes I have only experimented a bit so far but had good luck. Just like the Konad plates there is a bit of practice and skill involved in applying the right motion and pressure to both the scraped imaged on the plate, to pick it up, and rolling it on your nail to transfer it to your nail nicely. Smearing of highly detailed images or skips in the image happens when not enough, or too much pressure is applied in both the plate and the nail stamping operations. Yes, work quickly for best results, yes, try different polishes, some work much better than others.
As far as using the Bundlemonster plates their aforementioned, perhaps lesser quality, stainless steel makes them slightly more flexible. I found you couldn't get a clean scrape when the plate was set on top of a mere double paper towel thickness on a table surface. The image would be smeary because you didn't get all the excess polish off the image due to a very slight flex in the plate on the slightly poofy paper towels (this would be a huge problem on a regular cloth towel) and the plate . Maybe the plate holder would help but I found holding the plate down flat with your other hand while making the scrape does the trick. Also using an old cutting board or some kind of more solid surface would keep the plate absolutely flat for the scrape. Also the metal scaper, doesn't flex at all so it doesn't follow the slight flexing of the plate when you scrape. Try using a credit card or one of those really thin plastic rewards card from a store that will flex into the image as you scrape it. These slight adjustments to use the Bundlemonster plates, even though they are a bit lesser quality than the Konad, will transfer the more detailed images without smearing.

title: Decent product!
text:
So I don’t own a blow dryer or a hair straightener. I know. I bought this to hopefully replace the need for both of them. Pictured: my hair styled when damp, my hair styled and natural side-by-side, and my hair styled when dry (tie-dye shirt).

Some pros: I have very wavy, long, fine hair, but a ton of it, and can dry/style my hair in under 30 minutes with this. Yes the brush size is huge, but with how much hair I have, I need it to be large. The style it produced was beautiful! I will be keeping this for sure!

Some cons: I deducted a star mainly because this brush doesn’t get very hot. I guess this could be a pro since it won’t damage your hair as much over time. But for me, I noticed that some parts of my hair were still wavy, and that the style didn’t hold perfectly over time.

Some tips: definitely use this tool on damp hair. It semi-straightened my dry hair, but the style did not hold over time and my hair went right back to wavy in an hour. I had to go over my damp hair a few times, but make sure to maintain tension when you pull. That’s the best way I was able to get my hair straight. Another reason I deducted a star was because I still feel like I need a flat iron to do touch ups—around my roots specifically. But this product is definitely better than using a flat iron all over!

Verdict: worth $20! Glad I purchased.

title: Cheap, flimsy, cosmetic bag that has limited hanging options and is not worth consideration in my opinion
text:

Items have a tendency of tilting outward in the pockets depending on the size of the item and are at risk of falling out. The detachable clear plastic tote at the bottom is a nice touch, but that is about it. The zippers are sticky.

In my opinion this cosmetic / travel organizer will not last at all. My biggest complaint is the hook for hanging. It is not a full-size hanger hook so there are a limited number of places to hang this. It can be hung on a wire shelf with holes (like a shower caddy or closet with wire inserts) but it does not hang on a shower rod or on a closet rod or any rod much thicker than a finger.

This cosmetic bag is not even worth consideration in my opinion.

title: Finally, some natural color!
text:
I'm pasty pale with freckles and will burn if I try to "tan." Plus, I don't care for the cancer risk. I've tried sunless tanners in the past and turned orange. I don't want to go to the spa for a spray tan because it's expensive.

I don't need a tan, just some color to keep from being so pasty. LOreal Sunless Sublime Glow Daily Moisturizer Fair Skin Tones worked great for me. I had a hint of tan color within a day, nice and even, and it got a little better each day. It didn't look weird on my fair skin. It was nice and subtle, without taking forever to emerge. The micro pearl flecks also gave me a nice immediate glow. By the way, on my face, I used LOreal Sunless Sublime Glow Daily Moisturizer Face for Fair Skin, which did not have the pearl flecks, but did have SPF 15. It doesn't give as much color, but that is okay because I wear makeup anyway.

Some people complain about the smell, but I think it depends on taste. I've seen in other reviews that it smells like tea, and it does a little. My husband doesn't even know what I'm putting on, but last night in bed, he commented that I smelled so good, and he kept sniffing me because he liked it better than those floral or fruity lotions. He had never complimented my lotion scent before!

It is great as a moisturizer, too, my dry skin feels nice and hydrated all day. It's a bonus that it is giving me a little color, too.

I give it five stars!
features: ["Light capturing micro-pearls accentuate your body's natural contours and give skin a soft, subtle radiance."]

text: I have extremely light blonde (basically clear) eyebrows so have been dying them for years. It dyes my blonde eyebrows dark for about two weeks, which is pretty standard for how often I had been redoing them. But what was really nice was I felt like it didn’t stain the skin as much. I always struggled to do it and go out soon after and would need a day for the skin stain to wear off, but this comes off the skin much easier. I also love that it is specifically formulated for the face and eyes and I don’t have to worry about the “Do not use around eyes” warning on beard dyes. It gives me much more piece of mind and looks amazing.

title: not as good as expected
text: So this will be by 4th razor since i first started shaving.  My first was a Remington triple head like this and worked great. Years later i got another Remington i did not like as much and it cut me so i kept goin back to the original. Then i got a regular flat screen one and that just cut me and not the hair it seemed.  So time and again I went back to that original Remington.  it was getting old and broken tho so i decided i needed and upgrade and i wanted one with a cleaning system for a decent price so i thought i'd give Norelco a try.  So the razor was simple enough to set up and use but the motor just seems weak to me.  It does not really cut me which i am grateful for but it also takes like 20 runs over the same spot to get 'most" of the hair which is incredibly annoying.  The beard trimmer is so poorly designed it barely functions, and the cleaning kit says it isn't even antibacterial which seems to defeat the purpose of having it.  And i'm not even convinced the cleaning fluid isn't irritating my skin. All in all im disappointed.  I thought for $80 i'd finally have a good razor.  I mean it's useable and ill keep tryin and see if i adjust but its definitely not the miracle device i expected and i've decided the flexible heads r just a gimmick.

title: Surprisingly beautiful
text:
I'm surprised how nice this wig is considering it was only $13. It looks exactly as pictured. I was hesitant to buy it because there aren't any reviews for some reason but I ordered another wig from Kamo several weeks ago and that wig is beautiful. I'm talking about the 24" teal wig that currently has 117 reviews, so I figured another wig from this seller would be good too even though it's half the price. This wig is supposed to be 4" longer than that one, however it seems a little shorter? It probably is technically longer. It's just not as full but it's not thin either. It does have some long layers which could be contributing to that. It doesn't have too much of an unnatural shine, it's soft, and so far it isn't shedding that much though it probably will a little given the price. For $13, I highly recommend this wig. I really like this seller as well. You get a free wig cap, some bobby pins, and a little card from Kamo. Plus the packaging is kind of cute.

I'm going to be using this as a cosplay wig in case you were wondering. Not sure if it'd be good as an everyday wig. I already have a very long black wig that's around the $65 range but it's not that comfortable and I prefer the fit of this one much more. I will be pinning this to my head like nobody's business though because I definitely see this falling off if I'm not careful.

Since I'm always skeptical of buying something that only has one review and I get a little frustrated when they don't include a picture even if the review is positive, I'll include a few. I have some pins holding it to the styrofoam head that are noticeable in the images and the wig got a little disheveled when handling it so I'm sorry if it isn't all that neat. I plan to straighten mine and style it but I figured I would get some pictures of it right out of the package before I do that. ^-^

title: Aifaifa poly gel kit
text:
I was so happy when I got this kit. I waited until the weekend to try out my new products to see how it would turn out. I love the way everything came in a little carrying case with all of the products inside, I thought that was nice!

So I decided that I wanted to do the poly gel and form my own fingernails. I read the instructions 2 times to make sure that I was doing the right thing, first thing I noticed was the tacky layer after you put on the base coat, second thing I noticed was that after I formed my nail in the dual form it would not stick to my finger. So what I did was take an alcohol pad to wipe off everything and start over again, once again I noticed that the poly gel would not stick to my finger after wiping the tacky layer off the base coat. The gel polishes are nice, even though they are NOT labeled with the color or sticker of the color on the bottle. I had to slightly put the color on the top with a tooth pick. The colors are very nice, I love, love, love the purple and I like the pick color. The green and pearl white NOT so much!!! The UV lamp that came with the set is cute and all, but it really does not dry the gel polish like it should on just one try. I had to stick my fingers in the lamp about 3 or 4 times just to make sure the gel polish was dry all the way. I liked all of the essentials that came with this kit as well... glitter, nail color strips, and the art film.

PROS: Art Work CONS: Nail Lamp (Too Small)
Glitter Polish Doesn't dry all the way on one try
Art Film No Slip Solution
Colors of poly gel Bottles of poly gel could be a little bigger
Name of Colors not bottles of gel polish
No Cuticle Pusher

But out of all that this kit is not bad for $25.

title: Better options available
text:
I ordered this and a Japanese style Facon in the same order, figuring I'd use my favorite daily and add the runner-up to my travel bag.

I like the weight and feel of this razor in your hand. I like that there is no folding handle to get in your way. I like that it holds a complete double edge razor without having to break one in half (because I often bend one half while doing so to the point they are unusable) and I'd rather not by half razors in case I want to load up the safety razor and use it. I also like the black finish, as its easy to keep clean with just a rinse while using it.

However, for a complete face shave, it just isn't my favorite. I like the way it feels in my hand, but not on my face. After one pasd, I don't want to use it for a second or third. Constant irritation.

I think this would be good for beard shaping, and touch ups around sideburns and the back of the neck, but its not even going into my travel bag alone. Ill use it, but I think ill make sure and keep a disposable or one of my older safety razors in the travel bag too.

description: ['Iso E Super is an aroma-chemical, which, on its own, is less of a fragrance than an effect. Almost transparent in colour it has a vague sweet cedarwood-like scent imparting a male, woodsy, musky type aroma. It is known as the invisible fragrance, and has also been likened to a modern day Love Potion No.9! The reason for this is that it has been known to mimic the action of human pheromones. Although not a pheromone itself, it has the effect of other people noticing you or your fragrance but not quite being able to put their finger on the reason why. This is because ordinary fragrances are designed to project themselves over a wide radius, whilst Iso E Super is designed to cling to the skin, swapping itself between opulence and simplicity, sometimes being quite noticeable, sometimes undetectable. The wearer may notice a subtle, velvety, woody note which will vanish, then re-surface after some time. More than this, she or he will notice the impact the fragrance has on other people, because Iso E Super lends an indefinable allure to the wearer. In fact, its effect is almost pheromonic.']

title: Don't believe the other reviews, this comb is legit. steel body and it does have magnets among other things
text: So i read the reviews before buying one, then i watched Daft's kickstarter video showing the features of the comb. I was alittle hesitant since it had mixed reviews. Well i got it in the mail today. First thing i did was pull it out of its packaging and tried to open it. It felt smooth but had alot of resistance and i couldnt tell if it had magnets or not. I was trying to compare the comb i got to the ones on their official website and it looks identical, and Its sold on amazon by the actual company, so it must be legit right? so how come these other reviewers are claiming its aluminum, and theres no magnets, and the body is flimsy? those people are full of Sheet. I grabbed a magnet i had and it attracted to the metal body telling me its steel, the shine the body has tells me its stainless steel so i dont have to worry about rust, then i got a steel screwdriver and touched it to the magnets that are in the comb head and yup those are some strong magnets, but how come it doesnt react like the one in their video? well theres a set/adjustment screw on the side of the body and all it took was a penny to loosen it slightly and the comb functioned EXACTLY like their video. I was able to push out the comb alittle and flick it open and it stays erect with those magnets, i was really impressed with the flicking action. Next up i started to analyze the frame of the comb. So i know its stainless steel but how durable is it? well i have strong man hands and i could barely flex the frame with my hands. That frame is hella strong and im confident the comb head will never get damaged from the frame failing. That other review where some desk jockey broke it must have been really fat and had it in his back pocket or it was a lie since im 325 lbs and it doesnt get bent in my back pocket when i sit down. Overall Im so damn impressed with this comb that im gonna make a review video on youtubes. Thanks Art for making a kickass comb at a great price.

title: Love How My Teeth Feel
text: There was a definite learning curve for this.  I’ve never owned either an electric toothbrush, or a water flosser.  First time out with the flosser, I got all wet.  I had to Google how to use one.  Apparently, it is a messy ordeal unless you’re very, very careful.  After the first couple of uses, I had the same issue referenced by other reviewers, that the water pressure would randomly be very low.  It seems the rubber seal that connects the tank to the inner workings of the machine does “grab” properly.  I’ve found that by taking the end of a standard toothbrush and gently pressing down on the seal before turning it on results in a machine that works normally every time.  I LOVE LOVE LOVE how water flossing, combined with the electric toothbrush leave my teeth!  The difference between this and just a standard toothbrush is palpable.  In fact, combined with the fact that I was 25 the first time I saw a dentist, I’m surprised I haven’t rotted my teeth out at this point.  It’s addictive how clean my teeth feel!  Oral hygiene has never been something I think about, it was just been something I had to do.  Now I actually look forward to it, just so I can run my tongue over my teeth to feel how clean they feel.
